<DOC><DOCNO> AP890825-0154 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1917EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-25 0398</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0409</SECOND><HEAD>Temperatures Drop in Northeast; Heat Wave in South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Summer vacationers donned overcoats in the Northeast and snowfell in Montana on Friday, while the deep South experienceduncomfortable summer heat.   Fall weather made an early appearance as temperatures fell to aslow as 29 degrees at East Haven, Vt. Warm coats were needed atop ofMount Washington, N.H., where temperatures were around 30 degreesand winds gusted over 60 mph.   Scattered frost is expected Saturday morning in the coldervalleys of northern New England and northeastern New York state.   Cold weather also the rule across the northern and centralRockies, with temperatures in the 50s and 60s.   Heavy rain since Wednesday has caused flooding in parts ofnorthwest Montana, where more than 2{ inches rain fell from noonThursday to noon Friday at Great Falls.   Heavy snow covered some mountain ranges in Montana. The BeartoothHighway southwest of Red Lodge was covered with 1 to 2 inches ofsnow Friday morning.   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from easternportions of the northern and central Plains across Arkansas and theGulf Coast to the southern Atlantic Coast.   Widespread thunderstorms drenched northern Florida. Athunderstorm doused Daytona Beach with almost an inch of rain in ahalf-hour.   A warm front extended from southern Missouri across northernKentucky to the Carolinas, separating cloudy and cool weather in theNorth from hot weather in the South.   Temperatures as high as the mid-90s and high humidity made thingsuncomfortable from south-central Texas across the lower MississippiValley to Georgia.   The low temperature in the lower 48 states Thursday morning was28 degrees at Gunnison, Colo. At 3 p.m. EDT, the low was 47 degreesat Yellowstone Park in Wyoming and the high 100 degrees atMontgomery, Ala.   Saturday's national forecast called for showers and thunderstormsover the upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the lower Ohio andTennessee valleys and Florida; and widely scattered thunderstormsover the northern Rockies, much of the Plains and the central GulfCoast.   Highs were expected to be in the 60s in northern Maine, westernMontana and along parts of the Pacific Coast; in the 90s in thesouthern Atlantic Coast, the Gulf Coast, the lower MississippiValley, the southern Plains and interior valleys of California; near100 in the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>